const rawHTML = `
<div class="c">

<!-- Hero -->
<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-k">Comparison &middot; Weight Loss &middot; Incretin Therapy</div>
  <h1>Retatrutide vs Semaglutide: Triple Agonist Head-to-Head</h1>
  <p class="sub">Semaglutide proved pharmacological weight loss could work. Retatrutide posted 24% body weight loss in Phase 2 by targeting three receptors instead of one. Here is what the clinical data actually shows and who each compound is best suited for.</p>
  <div class="pills">
    <span class="pill">GLP-1 &middot; GIP &middot; Glucagon</span>
    <span class="pill">Phase 2 vs FDA-Approved</span>
    <span class="pill">Weight Loss &middot; Liver Fat</span>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Stats -->
<div class="sr">
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c1">24.2%</div><div class="l">Retatrutide<br>Weight Loss</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c2">14.9%</div><div class="l">Semaglutide<br>Weight Loss</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c3">3</div><div class="l">Receptors Targeted<br>by Retatrutide</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c4">82%</div><div class="l">Liver Fat<br>Reduction</div></div>
</div>

<p>Semaglutide changed everything. <a href="/articles/semaglutide-weight-loss-guide">Wegovy and Ozempic</a> proved that pharmacological <a href="/articles/best-peptides-for-fat-loss">weight loss</a> could actually work at scale, with patients dropping 15% of their body weight on a weekly injection.</p>

<p>But semaglutide might already be getting surpassed. <a href="/articles/retatrutide-complete-guide">Retatrutide</a>, Eli Lilly's triple agonist, posted 24.2% body weight loss at the highest dose in Phase 2. That is approaching bariatric surgery territory without the scalpel.</p>

<div class="d">
  <div class="s">Bottom Line Up Front</div>
  <p>Retatrutide produces roughly 60% more weight loss than semaglutide in clinical trials. But semaglutide has years of real-world data and proven cardiovascular benefits. The triple agonist wins on raw numbers. Semaglutide wins on track record.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== HEAD-TO-HEAD TABLE ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Head-to-Head Comparison at a Glance</h2>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Semaglutide (Wegovy)</th><th>Retatrutide</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Receptor Targets</strong></td><td>GLP-1 only</td><td class="g">GLP-1 + GIP + Glucagon</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Generation</strong></td><td>1st gen</td><td class="g">3rd gen</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Max Weight Loss</strong></td><td>~15&ndash;16% (68 wk)</td><td class="g">~24.2% (48 wk)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Liver Fat Reduction</strong></td><td class="y">Modest</td><td class="g">82%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>FDA Approved</strong></td><td class="g">Yes (2021)</td><td class="r">No (Phase 3 underway)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>CV Outcomes Data</strong></td><td class="g">Yes (SELECT trial)</td><td class="r">Not yet</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Dosing</strong></td><td>2.4 mg weekly SC</td><td>Up to 12 mg weekly SC</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Developer</strong></td><td>Novo Nordisk</td><td>Eli Lilly</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Real-World Data</strong></td><td class="g">Years</td><td class="r">Phase 2 only</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The table tells a split story. Retatrutide wins on efficacy metrics across the board. Semaglutide wins on everything that requires time: approval, safety data, cardiovascular outcomes.</p>

<!-- ========== MECHANISMS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>How They Work: The Mechanism Difference</h2>

<p>Semaglutide and retatrutide both belong to the incretin-based therapy family. But they activate very different receptor profiles, and that difference explains the gap in clinical results.</p>

<div class="cd cb">
  <div class="tg">Single Agonist</div>
  <h3>Semaglutide: GLP-1 Only</h3>
  <p>Semaglutide mimics glucagon-like peptide-1, a gut hormone that slows gastric emptying, reduces appetite through hypothalamic signaling, enhances insulin secretion, and suppresses glucagon release. Its long half-life (about 7 days) allows once-weekly dosing.</p>
  <p>The FDA approved it for type 2 diabetes (Ozempic) in 2017 and chronic weight management (Wegovy) in 2021. The STEP trial program demonstrated approximately 15&ndash;17% weight loss over 68 weeks (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33567185/">Wilding et al., 2021</a>).</p>
</div>

<div class="cd ct">
  <div class="tg">Triple Agonist</div>
  <h3>Retatrutide: GLP-1 + GIP + Glucagon</h3>
  <p>Retatrutide hits three receptors simultaneously. GLP-1 provides the appetite suppression foundation. GIP amplifies incretin effects and improves insulin sensitivity. Glucagon increases energy expenditure through thermogenesis and targets liver fat directly.</p>
  <p>The critical difference: retatrutide does not just reduce caloric intake. It actively increases caloric expenditure, hitting both sides of the energy balance equation at the same time.</p>
</div>

<!-- SVG Mechanism Diagram -->
<div class="svg-box">
  <div class="st">Receptor Targeting Comparison</div>
  <div class="ss">Single vs. dual vs. triple agonism across the incretin therapy evolution</div>
  <svg viewBox="0 0 700 260" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <!-- Semaglutide -->
    <rect x="20" y="40" width="200" height="180" rx="12" fill="#E8EEF9" stroke="#2956A6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="120" y="30" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Lora,serif" font-size="14" fill="#18182A" font-weight="600">Semaglutide</text>
    <rect x="50" y="70" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#2956A6"/>
    <text x="120" y="95" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#fff" font-weight="600">GLP-1</text>
    <rect x="50" y="125" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#D9D6CE"/>
    <text x="120" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#86869A" font-weight="500">GIP (inactive)</text>
    <rect x="50" y="180" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#D9D6CE"/>
    <text x="120" y="205" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#86869A" font-weight="500">Glucagon (inactive)</text>
    <!-- Tirzepatide -->
    <rect x="250" y="40" width="200" height="180" rx="12" fill="#F3ECF8" stroke="#6E3B8A" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="350" y="30" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Lora,serif" font-size="14" fill="#18182A" font-weight="600">Tirzepatide</text>
    <rect x="280" y="70" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#2956A6"/>
    <text x="350" y="95" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#fff" font-weight="600">GLP-1</text>
    <rect x="280" y="125" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#6E3B8A"/>
    <text x="350" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#fff" font-weight="600">GIP</text>
    <rect x="280" y="180" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#D9D6CE"/>
    <text x="350" y="205" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#86869A" font-weight="500">Glucagon (inactive)</text>
    <!-- Retatrutide -->
    <rect x="480" y="40" width="200" height="180" rx="12" fill="#E4F5EF" stroke="#187A62" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="580" y="30" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Lora,serif" font-size="14" fill="#18182A" font-weight="600">Retatrutide</text>
    <rect x="510" y="70" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#2956A6"/>
    <text x="580" y="95" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#fff" font-weight="600">GLP-1</text>
    <rect x="510" y="125" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#6E3B8A"/>
    <text x="580" y="150" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#fff" font-weight="600">GIP</text>
    <rect x="510" y="180" width="140" height="40" rx="8" fill="#187A62"/>
    <text x="580" y="205" text-anchor="middle" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="12" fill="#fff" font-weight="600">Glucagon</text>
    <!-- Arrows -->
    <line x1="225" y1="130" x2="245" y2="130" stroke="#86869A" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
    <line x1="455" y1="130" x2="475" y2="130" stroke="#86869A" stroke-width="2" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
    <defs><marker id="arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 Z" fill="#86869A"/></marker></defs>
  </svg>
</div>

<p>Each generation adds a receptor. Semaglutide targets one. <a href="/articles/tirzepatide-complete-guide">Tirzepatide</a> targets two. Retatrutide targets all three. The glucagon component is what separates retatrutide from everything else on the market.</p>

<div class="cd ca">
  <div class="tg">Key Insight</div>
  <h3>Why Glucagon Matters</h3>
  <p>Glucagon increases energy expenditure through thermogenesis, promotes hepatic fat oxidation (burning liver fat directly), mobilizes fat from adipose tissue, and reduces food intake through pathways separate from GLP-1. It is the reason retatrutide can attack both sides of the energy equation.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== CLINICAL TRIALS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Clinical Trial Data: The Numbers</h2>

<h3>Semaglutide: STEP 1 Trial</h3>

<p>The STEP 1 trial enrolled 1,961 adults with obesity or overweight. At 68 weeks with semaglutide 2.4 mg weekly (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33567185/">Wilding et al., 2021</a>):</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Outcome</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Placebo</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Mean weight loss</strong></td><td class="g">14.9%</td><td>2.4%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lost &gt;10% body weight</strong></td><td class="g">69.1%</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lost &gt;20% body weight</strong></td><td class="g">32.0%</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>A third of participants losing over 20% was unprecedented at the time. That was the benchmark semaglutide set.</p>

<h3>Retatrutide: Phase 2 Trial</h3>

<p>The Phase 2 trial enrolled 338 adults with obesity. At 48 weeks on the highest dose (12 mg weekly) (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37351564/">Jastreboff et al., 2023</a>):</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Outcome</th><th>Retatrutide 12 mg</th><th>Placebo</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Mean weight loss</strong></td><td class="g">24.2%</td><td>2.1%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lost &gt;10% body weight</strong></td><td class="g">93%</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lost &gt;15% body weight</strong></td><td class="g">83%</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lost &gt;20% body weight</strong></td><td class="g">63%</td><td>N/A</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Nearly two-thirds of participants on the highest dose lost over 20% of their body weight. The weight loss curve had not plateaued at 48 weeks, meaning longer treatment could produce even greater reductions.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Dose-Response Data</div>
  <p>Even retatrutide's lower doses (8 mg) outperformed semaglutide's best results. The 8 mg group hit 22.8% weight loss. The dose-response curve suggests the triple mechanism is genuinely superior, not just marginally better.</p>
</div>

<h3>Weight Loss by Retatrutide Dose</h3>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Dose (Weekly)</th><th>Weight Loss</th><th>~Pounds Lost (at 240 lb)</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>1 mg</strong></td><td>8.7%</td><td>~21 lb</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>4 mg</strong></td><td>17.1&ndash;17.5%</td><td>~41&ndash;42 lb</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>8 mg</strong></td><td class="g">22.8%</td><td>~55 lb</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>12 mg</strong></td><td class="g">24.2%</td><td>~58 lb</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<!-- ========== SIDE EFFECTS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Side Effect Profiles</h2>

<p>More potent weight loss often means more side effects. The picture here is more nuanced than you might expect.</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Side Effect</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Retatrutide</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Nausea</strong></td><td class="y">44%</td><td class="y">~45% (highest dose)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Diarrhea</strong></td><td class="y">30%</td><td class="y">~35%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Vomiting</strong></td><td class="y">24%</td><td>~17%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Constipation</strong></td><td class="y">24%</td><td>Less characterized</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Discontinuation Rate</strong></td><td>~7%</td><td>~6% (highest dose)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>GI side effects dominate both compounds. They follow the same pattern: worst during dose escalation, improving over time.</p>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4>Blood Sugar Concern</h4>
    <p>Glucagon's primary job is raising blood sugar, so you might expect problems with retatrutide. In practice, the GLP-1 and GIP components counteract this effect. Retatrutide actually improved glycemic control, with HbA1c dropping by about 2 percentage points.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4>Heart Rate Effects</h4>
    <p>Heart rate increases were noted in some retatrutide participants. <a href="/articles/semaglutide-weight-loss-guide">Semaglutide</a> also shows mild heart rate increases. Both will need continued monitoring in Phase 3 and post-market surveillance.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="d-a">
  <div class="s">Safety Summary</div>
  <p>Roughly comparable GI profiles. Neither compound shows a clear safety advantage at this stage, though semaglutide has far more long-term data behind it.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== MUSCLE PRESERVATION ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Muscle Preservation</h2>

<p>When you lose weight rapidly, a significant portion can come from lean tissue. That is bad for metabolic health, physical function, and long-term weight maintenance.</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Retatrutide</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Lean mass lost</strong></td><td class="r">~39% of total weight lost</td><td class="y">Potentially less (early data)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td><td>Calorie reduction only</td><td class="g">Calorie reduction + fat oxidation via glucagon</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Body comp data</strong></td><td>Published (STEP 1)</td><td class="y">Pending (Phase 3)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>Glucagon promotes fat oxidation specifically. Preclinical data suggests that triple agonism may shift the ratio of fat-to-lean mass loss in a more favorable direction.</p>

<div class="d-r">
  <div class="s">Important Note</div>
  <p>Detailed body composition data from large Phase 3 trials has not been published yet. Regardless of which drug you take, resistance training and adequate protein intake are non-negotiable for preserving muscle mass.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== METABOLIC BENEFITS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Metabolic Benefits Beyond Weight Loss</h2>

<h3>Liver Fat</h3>

<div class="cd ct">
  <div class="tg">Standout Result</div>
  <h3>Retatrutide's Liver Fat Effect</h3>
  <p>Retatrutide reduced liver fat by 82% at 48 weeks. Over 80% of participants no longer qualified for a MASLD diagnosis. Semaglutide produces only modest liver fat reduction, mostly as a secondary effect of weight loss. Retatrutide's glucagon component targets hepatic fat directly.</p>
</div>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Retatrutide</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Liver fat reduction</strong></td><td class="y">Modest</td><td class="g">82% at 48 weeks</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Mechanism</strong></td><td>Indirect (weight loss)</td><td class="g">Direct (glucagon targets hepatic fat)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>MASLD resolution</strong></td><td>Being studied</td><td class="g">80%+ no longer qualified</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Cardiovascular Risk</h3>

<p>Semaglutide has proven cardiovascular benefits. The SELECT trial showed a 20% reduction in major adverse cardiovascular events in people with obesity and established cardiovascular disease (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37952131/">Lincoff et al., 2023</a>).</p>

<p>Retatrutide has no cardiovascular outcomes data yet. It will take years to match what semaglutide has established. This is not a minor gap. For patients with existing heart disease, semaglutide's proven CV benefit is a major differentiator.</p>

<h3>Blood Sugar Control</h3>

<p>Both compounds significantly improve glycemic control with 1.5 to 2 percentage point HbA1c reductions. Retatrutide's triple mechanism may offer slightly better glucose regulation, but the difference is not dramatic based on available data.</p>

<!-- ========== COST AND AVAILABILITY ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Cost and Availability</h2>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Factor</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Retatrutide</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Available now</strong></td><td class="g">Yes (Ozempic/Wegovy)</td><td class="r">No</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Monthly cost</strong></td><td>$900&ndash;$1,350 list</td><td>Expected $1,000+</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Insurance coverage</strong></td><td class="y">Varies widely</td><td class="r">N/A</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Generic available</strong></td><td class="r">No (patent expires 2032)</td><td class="r">N/A</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Expected approval</strong></td><td class="g">Already approved</td><td class="y">2027&ndash;2028 earliest</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Research chemical</strong></td><td>Compounded versions available</td><td>Available from peptide suppliers</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>This is semaglutide's biggest practical advantage. It exists. You can get a prescription today. Retatrutide is still in the clinical pipeline.</p>

<!-- ========== WHO SHOULD CHOOSE WHAT ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Which Is Better for Whom?</h2>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="cd cb">
    <div class="tg">Established Choice</div>
    <h3>Choose Semaglutide If:</h3>
    <p><strong>You need treatment now.</strong> FDA-approved and available today with established clinical pathways.</p>
    <p><strong>Safety data matters most.</strong> Years of real-world evidence across millions of patients.</p>
    <p><strong>Cardiovascular protection is a priority.</strong> The SELECT trial proved a 20% MACE reduction.</p>
    <p><strong>You have type 2 diabetes.</strong> Decades of incretin therapy data support its use.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="cd ct">
    <div class="tg">Maximum Efficacy</div>
    <h3>Choose Retatrutide If:</h3>
    <p><strong>Maximum weight loss is the goal.</strong> 24% vs 15% for semaglutide. The gap is significant.</p>
    <p><strong>Fatty liver is a major concern.</strong> 82% liver fat reduction in trials is unmatched.</p>
    <p><strong>You have plateaued on GLP-1 monotherapy.</strong> The triple mechanism offers additional pathways.</p>
    <p><strong>You can tolerate uncertainty.</strong> Still experimental with no long-term data available.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="d-p">
  <div class="s">Honest Take</div>
  <p>If you had to bet on the gold standard for obesity treatment in 5 years, the smart money is on retatrutide or something like it. Triple agonism addresses more of the obesity puzzle than single agonism. But semaglutide earned its status for a reason: it works, it is studied extensively, and it is available right now.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== TIRZEPATIDE CONTEXT ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Where Does Tirzepatide Fit?</h2>

<p><a href="/articles/tirzepatide-complete-guide">Tirzepatide</a> (Mounjaro/Zepbound) is the middle step in the evolution from single to triple agonism. It is FDA-approved and available now, making it a strong alternative to both compounds.</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Semaglutide</th><th>Tirzepatide</th><th>Retatrutide</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Targets</strong></td><td>GLP-1</td><td>GLP-1 + GIP</td><td class="g">GLP-1 + GIP + Glucagon</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Weight loss</strong></td><td>~15%</td><td>~21%</td><td class="g">~24%</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>FDA approved</strong></td><td class="g">Yes</td><td class="g">Yes</td><td class="r">No</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Liver fat</strong></td><td class="y">Modest</td><td class="y">Moderate</td><td class="g">Substantial</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>If semaglutide is not producing sufficient results and you want something available today, tirzepatide is the logical next step before retatrutide reaches the market.</p>

<!-- ========== PRACTICAL CONSIDERATIONS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Practical Considerations</h2>

<h3>Dose Titration</h3>

<p>Both compounds require careful dose escalation. Starting at the full dose is a recipe for severe nausea and possible discontinuation. The principle is the same for both: start low, increase slowly, let your body adapt.</p>

<div class="g3">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4>Semaglutide Schedule</h4>
    <p>Start at 0.25 mg weekly for 4 weeks. Increase to 0.5 mg, then 1 mg, then 1.7 mg, then 2.4 mg. Each step lasts 4 weeks minimum. Full dose is typically reached by week 16&ndash;20.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4>Retatrutide Schedule</h4>
    <p>Phase 2 used a similar stepwise escalation. Started at low doses and titrated upward over several months. The exact clinical titration protocol will be finalized after Phase 3 completion.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4>General Principle</h4>
    <p>If nausea is severe at any step, stay at the current dose for an additional 2&ndash;4 weeks before increasing. Slower titration almost always improves tolerability with both compounds.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h3>Combining with Lifestyle Changes</h3>

<p>Neither compound works optimally in isolation. Resistance training preserves lean mass during rapid weight loss. Protein intake of 1.0&ndash;1.2 g per pound of lean body mass supports muscle maintenance and satiety.</p>

<p>The drugs handle appetite suppression. You handle the quality of what you eat when you do eat. Smaller appetite does not mean you can ignore nutrition. If anything, it makes every meal count more because you are eating less overall.</p>

<div class="cd cp">
  <div class="tg">Research Context</div>
  <h3>What Phase 3 Will Tell Us</h3>
  <p>Retatrutide's Phase 3 program (TRIUMPH trials) will enroll thousands of participants across multiple studies. We will get definitive data on long-term weight loss sustainability, detailed body composition analysis, cardiovascular outcomes, liver fat effects at scale, and safety across diverse populations.</p>
  <p>Until those results are published, all comparisons with semaglutide carry the caveat that retatrutide's data comes from a much smaller patient pool over a shorter timeframe. Phase 2 results are promising. They are not proof.</p>
</div>

<h3>Storage and Administration</h3>

<p>Both compounds are administered as subcutaneous injections, typically in the abdomen, thigh, or upper arm. Both require refrigeration. Semaglutide comes in pre-filled pens (Ozempic/Wegovy) with straightforward dosing. Retatrutide, when available as a research compound, requires reconstitution and insulin syringes.</p>

<p>Injection technique matters less than consistency. Pick a day of the week and stick with it. Rotate injection sites to avoid lipodystrophy.</p>

<!-- ========== FAQ ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq">
  <details>
    <summary>Can I switch from semaglutide to retatrutide?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>Once retatrutide is approved, switching should be feasible under medical supervision. The transition protocol has not been established yet. Given the overlapping GLP-1 activity, your body would not encounter a completely unfamiliar mechanism. A dose escalation period would still be necessary.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Is retatrutide safe?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>Phase 2 data shows a favorable safety profile, but Phase 2 trials are small (338 participants). Phase 3 trials with thousands of participants will provide a much clearer picture. No red flags have emerged so far, but "no red flags in a small trial" is not the same as "proven safe in large populations."</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Will I regain weight after stopping either drug?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>Probably some, yes. The STEP 1 extension trial showed participants regained about two-thirds of lost weight within a year of stopping semaglutide (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35441470/">Wilding et al., 2022</a>). These drugs manage obesity. They do not cure it. Long-term treatment may be necessary for sustained results.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Does retatrutide cause more nausea than semaglutide?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>The GI side effect rates are roughly comparable at effective doses. Proper dose titration (starting low and increasing gradually) significantly reduces nausea with both compounds. Neither has a clear advantage on tolerability.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Can I take either of these with other peptides?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>Many people combine GLP-1 agonists with GH peptides like tesamorelin or ipamorelin. There is no established contraindication, but there is also limited data on interactions. Work with a knowledgeable provider if you are considering combinations.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Is the weight loss from retatrutide sustainable?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>We do not know yet. Long-term data beyond 48 weeks is not available. If the pattern follows other incretin therapies, weight regain after cessation is likely. But while on treatment, weight loss was ongoing at 48 weeks, meaning longer treatment may produce even greater reductions.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>What about compounded or research-grade versions?</summary>
    <div class="fa">
      <p>Both compounds are available through peptide suppliers as research chemicals. Compounded semaglutide has become widely available through telehealth clinics. Retatrutide is available primarily as a research chemical. Quality and purity vary significantly between suppliers. Third-party testing is essential regardless of source.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
</div>

<!-- ========== BOTTOM LINE ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>Semaglutide opened the door. It proved pharmacological obesity treatment could produce clinically meaningful <a href="/articles/best-peptides-for-fat-loss">weight loss</a> with an acceptable safety profile.</p>

<p>Retatrutide is walking through it with better numbers. Nearly 25% body weight loss, superior liver fat reduction, potentially better muscle preservation, and a mechanism that addresses energy expenditure in addition to appetite suppression.</p>

<div class="sr">
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c2">~60%</div><div class="l">More Weight Loss<br>Than Semaglutide</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c1">82%</div><div class="l">Liver Fat<br>Reduction</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c4">2027+</div><div class="l">Earliest Possible<br>FDA Approval</div></div>
</div>

<p>Triple agonism is not just an incremental improvement. It is a meaningful leap forward in how we treat obesity pharmacologically.</p>

<p>The caveat is time. Retatrutide needs Phase 3 data, FDA approval, cardiovascular outcomes studies, and years of post-market surveillance before it can match semaglutide's evidence base. If you need treatment now, <a href="/articles/semaglutide-weight-loss-guide">semaglutide</a> and <a href="/articles/tirzepatide-complete-guide">tirzepatide</a> are excellent options with strong data behind them.</p>

<p>But if you are watching the field and wondering what comes next, retatrutide is the answer. The triple agonist wins on the science. Now it just needs to prove it at scale.</p>

